<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Season 5, Episode 8 </strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Abbots: Remember when your mother told you not to make a nasty face because a cold wind would come along and freeze it in place? And you didnât believe her? And then years went by, and youâre staring into the face of Susan MacClare, Marchioness of Flintshire (Phoebe Nicholls), and you realize your mother was right all along? </p>
<div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><h6 class="kicker"><a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/category/television/tv-recaps/watching-downton-abbey/">'Downton Abbey'</a></h6><p class="summary">The PBS costume drama set in England.</p><ul class="recent-headlines"><li><a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/01/downton-abbey-recap-in-the-finale-mary-meets-mr-handsome-who-could-care-less/">&#8216;Downton Abbey&#8217; Recap: In the Finale, Mary Meets Mr. Handsome</a></li><li><a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/02/22/downton-abbey-recap-yes-its-called-the-hornby-hotel/">&#8216;Downton Abbey&#8217; Recap: Yes, It&#8217;s Called the Hornby Hotel</a></li><li><a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/02/15/downton-abbey-recap-the-crawleys-should-have-sent-their-regrets/">&#8216;Downton Abbey&#8217; Recap: The Crawleys Should Have Sent Their Regrets</a></li></ul></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was an ill wind indeed that fixed Lady F.âs features into that attitude of pouchy petulance, and it must have done a number on her soul, too. From the moment she turns up for her daughterâs wedding, she exerts a kind of Dementor spell on the proceedings, draining joy from every pore. She kvetches about everything from the Bombay journey to the Southampton train; she insults her daughterâs soon-to-be in-laws; she springs the news of her impending divorce at the worst possible time; and for good measure she frames the groom.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Of course, she had a little help with that last part. Didnât you feel a premonitory chill, Abbots, when you learned that Atticus Aldridge (Matt Barber) was planning a stag party? At the Hornby Hotel? Sure enough, Atticus is inveigled by a call girl into what seem like compromising positions for a hidden photographer. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I would have expected some kind of camera flash, but maybe my attention was just waylaid by that alarmingly deep furrow in Atticusâs abdomen. At any rate, I roused myself quickly enough to wonder if the framer-upper was Lord Sinderby (James Faulkner), who wants <span id="more-348019"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> to keep his dynasty from absorbing âthe same prejudices as everyone else who shops at Harrodsâ and who has scant patience for that âlittle shiksaâ Rose (Lily James).  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">(Here is where I pause to consult the Abbot hive-mind. Wasnât âshiksaâ a far more insulting term back in the 1920s â i.e., roughly synonymous with âslutâ? Does Lord S. really think Rose hangs out in the same joints as the ladyâs maid, Denker (Sue Johnston)?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Well, Lord S. may have a distaste for cardsharps, undercooked fish and divorce (which he equates with âweakness, degradation, scandal, failureâ), but he draws the line at sting operations. Which leaves only one other suspect, Abbots, and it may be that Susanâs face has more give than I thought, because I could swear it grew even frownier when her stratagems failed to halt true loveâs course. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAm I just expected to be a good loser?â she asks. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs too late for that, my dear,â murmurs Aunt Violet, the Dowager Countess (Maggie Smith).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In other news, poor Anna (Joanne Froggatt) is languishing in jail, an accused murderess. And if youâre wondering why I buried that lead sentence, itâs because weâre all in jail with her, too â the Penitentiary of Moribund Plot Lines. Iâm weary, Abbots. Weary of Mr. Green and the pained, darting glances his name induces. Weary of the steady drip of police inquiry. And weary, too, of having our collective intelligence insulted. Even if we accept the notion that Scotland Yard has waged a massive two-year manhunt on behalf of a valet, why would the police wait so long to put Anna in the lineup? How would a witness be able to identify her after all that time? How could she be arrested simply because she was seen âon the pavement near Mr. Green just before he fellâ? Wouldnât someone have to catch her in the act of shoving him? Doesnât anybody at Scotland Yard have better things to do?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Clearly, the Bateses are the characters whom Baron Fellowes most loves to torment, but suffering doesnât necessarily make people more interesting. Look at drippy, dreary Edith (Laura Carmichael), who, under plot duress, has reverted to a maternal cipher. All the more reason to treasure the moment when she catches her father pining over his son-in-law-never-to-be, Tony Gillingham (Tom Cullen). âGive it up, Papa,â she snaps. âItâs a pipe dream.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Edith! Youâre alive!</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Best scene: </strong>The Flintshire-Sinderby dinner. Susan comes armed for battle with an anti-Semitic barb for each member of the groomâs family: âWhat a peculiar name. â¦Do you have any English blood? â¦ I always think of you as nomads, drifting around the world.â But then she makes the mistake of asking if they have trouble getting staff workers. âNot very,â  responds Lady Sinderby (Penny Downie). âBut then, weâre Jewish, so we pay well.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As my kids would say: You just got pwned, Susan. Indeed, after long and careful deliberation, I have concluded that Lady S. is my new Best Gal Pal. The deal was clinched the moment she cooed in her husbandâs ear: âIf you do anything to stop this marriage, anything at all, I will leave you. And then youâll have a scandal worthy of the name.â Lady S.? Letâs you and me make a night of it with Mabel Lane Fox (Catherine Steadman) and close down the Hornby bar. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Best line:</strong> I quite liked Maryâs (Michelle Dockery) gibe at Edith: âWhy does she have to carry on as if sheâd invented motherhood?â That pretty much anatomizes the showâs Edith Problem. Denker is also bringing it with Spratt (Jeremy Swift): âHow else would you like to be summoned? By Joshuaâs trumpet?â But I must bow to Shrimpie (Peter Egan) and his economy of words. When Susan tries to wrest damning evidence from his grip, he need only snarl (and not for the first time, Iâm guessing), âGet down, you cat!â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>This weekâs drinking game:</strong> A bowl of Regentâs Punch for every time Daisy (Sophie McShera) whines. Oh, what a little rain cloud sheâs become, Abbots! âSometimes I think my life has no possibilities at all. â¦ I feel so resentful, so discontented. Itâs as if my whole life were a prison I have to go back to. â¦ How empty my lifeâs been. â¦â Hey, toots? Give it a rest.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>I Google so you donât have to (part 1):</strong> The heiress Hannah Rothschild did indeed marry the 5th Earl of Rosebery in 1878 and remained devoted to him until her death at 39.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>I Google so you donât have to (part 2):</strong> In the 1919 Amritsar massacre, British soldiers under the command of Brig. Gen. Reginald Dyer fired into a crowd of nonviolent Indian protesters, killing hundreds. It is considered a seminal event in the dismantling of British colonial rule.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Department of other stuff â¦</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">* Speaking of India â¦ was I wrong to hope Susan would bring OâBrien back with her? I still miss that soap-wielding monster with her aura of unappeasable rage. Alas, Baron Fellowes did some fancy footwork and got OâBrien reassigned to âthe new governorâs wife.â And if that doesnât bring down the British Raj, nothing will.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">* With what agonizing slowness does the sun rise on Robert Crawley (Hugh Bonneville). Frowning over Marigold, he ponders: âThere is something about her. â¦ I donât know, a sense of dÃ©jÃ  vu. â¦ Canât quite put my finger on it. â¦â But he finally does, bless him, and letâs give him credit for admitting how rare that is and for looking so adorable as he Crawleys on the floor with his grandkids. âWhat would my father say?â he wonders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">* Itâs nobodyâs fault, exactly, but I havenât been able to take Prince Kuragin (Rade Serbedzija) seriously ever since my friend Mary Kay pointed out his resemblance to the Worldâs Most Interesting Man in the Dos Equis ad campaign. When he mutters things like âI know my own bearingsâ and âI donât seek scandal, only love,â I keep imagining him doing photo shoots for premium vodka brands. It might help, I suppose, if I felt even a crackle of sumfin-sumfin with him and Violet, but I think sheâs got more going on with Spratt. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">* Denker turns out to be quite the good-time gal, stumbling back in a drunken haze from a place called the Velvet Violin and singing â what else? â âItâs a Long Way to Tipperary.â Denker tries to put her hooks into the temporary servant boy Andy (Michael Fox), but Thomas (Rob James-Collier), with his unerring eye for ingenuous jug-eared lads, comes to the rescue. And hereâs where I want to remind Baron Fellowes that Thomas is in London now â not too far from Bloomsbury â and could be hooking up with Lytton Strachey or E.M. Forster or, depending on the night, John Maynard Keynes. Is Andy really as good as it gets? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">*  Daisyâs father-in-law, Mr. Mason (Paul Copley), may be the most praiseworthy, least engrossing character in âDowntonâ history.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">* Gorgeous music as the Crawleys hit the road to London. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">* Some Abbots have theorized that Lady Mary and Tom Branson (Allen Leech) are being nudged toward the altar. Letâs eavesdrop. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mary: âYouâre about to leave and take Sybbie with you. Itâs too much to bear. â¦Itâs a dagger in my heart. I donât know what Iâll do without you.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Tom: âWe have our memories, you and I.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mary: âBut now youâll take them away with you to Boston.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Tom: âAnd Iâll cherish them when I get there.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Best-case scenario: Tom drags Mary to America and gets her to eat. They intermarry with the Fitzgeralds and the Kennedys. Their great-grandkids shovel unholy amounts of snow.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So speak, Abbots. Will Tom ever leave? Ever? Will Daisy pass her exams and drop Downton like an old shoe? Will Andy somehow worm his way into her job? Will Michael Gregsonâs name be on Riponâs next war memorial? Will Lady Mary discover she <em>is</em> the Queen of the Upper Nile? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Already getting teary. Just one more!</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Louis Bayard is the author of âRooseveltâs Beast,â âThe Pale Blue Eyeâ and âMr. Timothy.â</em></p>
